Explain child-to-parent communication using custom events with examples.
Companies that asked this: Salesforce, TCS, Infosys, Capgemini, Accenture, IBM, Wipro

Answer:
Child-to-parent communication in LWC is achieved using custom events. The child component dispatches a custom event with data, and the parent component listens for that event and handles it.

CustomEvent Syntax

const event = new CustomEvent('eventname', {
    detail: data,           // Data to pass (any type)
    bubbles: boolean,       // Default: false
    composed: boolean,      // Default: false  
    cancelable: boolean     // Default: false
});
this.dispatchEvent(event);
detail: The actual data you want to send to the parent component (string, object, array, etc.)

bubbles: Allows the event to travel up through parent elements in the DOM tree

composed: Lets the event cross shadow DOM boundaries (useful for deeply nested components)

cancelable: Enables the event to be stopped/cancelled using preventDefault() method



Basic Example

Child Component (childComponent.js)

import { LightningElement } from 'lwc';
export default class ChildComponent extends LightningElement {
    handleButtonClick() {
        // Create custom event with data
        const event = new CustomEvent('datapass', {
            detail: { 
                message: 'Hello from child!',
                value: 42 
            }
        });
        
        // Dispatch the event
        this.dispatchEvent(event);
    }
}
Child Template (childComponent.html)

<template>
    <lightning-button 
        label="Send Data to Parent" 
        onclick={handleButtonClick}>
    </lightning-button>
</template>
Parent Template (parentComponent.html)

<template>
    <div>
        <h3>Parent Component</h3>
        <p>Message: {receivedMessage}</p>
        <p>Value: {receivedValue}</p>
        
        <!-- Listen for custom event -->
        <c-child-component ondatapass={handleDataFromChild}>
        </c-child-component>
    </div>
</template>
Parent Component (parentComponent.js)

import { LightningElement } from 'lwc';
export default class ParentComponent extends LightningElement {
    receivedMessage = '';
    receivedValue = 0;
    handleDataFromChild(event) {
        // Access data from event.detail
        this.receivedMessage = event.detail.message;
        this.receivedValue = event.detail.value;
        
        console.log('Received:', event.detail);
    }
}

ðŸ’¡ Interview Tips:

Emphasize event.detail - Where data is passed

Show event naming conventions - Clear, descriptive names

Mention bubbling - For multi-level communication
